Installed and configured Vercel Speed Insights for the Create React App project

## Changes Made:

### 1. Package Installation
- Installed `@vercel/speed-insights@2.0.0` using pnpm
- Updated package.json with the new dependency

### 2. Code Integration
- Added import statement in src/App.tsx: `import { SpeedInsights } from '@vercel/speed-insights/react'`
- Placed `<SpeedInsights />` component at the end of the main App div, just before the closing tag
- This follows the official Vercel documentation for React/Create React App integration

### 3. Files Modified
- `src/App.tsx` - Added SpeedInsights import and component
- `package.json` - Added @vercel/speed-insights dependency
- `pnpm-lock.yaml` - Updated with new dependency lock information

### 4. Verification
- ✅ Build completed successfully without errors
- ✅ No linting errors introduced
- ✅ Code follows existing patterns and preserves all existing functionality

## Implementation Notes:

The implementation follows the latest Vercel Speed Insights quickstart documentation (fetched from https://vercel.com/docs/speed-insights/quickstart). For a Create React App with TypeScript:

1. Used the React-specific import: `@vercel/speed-insights/react`
2. Placed the component at the root level to track all page performance metrics
3. The component is self-contained and requires no additional configuration

The Speed Insights component will automatically start collecting Core Web Vitals and performance metrics once the application is deployed to Vercel and Speed Insights is enabled in the Vercel dashboard.

## Next Steps (Post-Deployment):

1. Enable Speed Insights in the Vercel dashboard for this project
2. Deploy the application using `vercel deploy` or via Git integration
3. Wait for user traffic to accumulate (Vercel recommends several days for meaningful data)
4. Access metrics via the Speed Insights section in the Vercel dashboard
